ht|b|cs|6|fp|1|at|^-{             Rule 15 and its Cousins              
      The Spades Have It — The Rule of 15      }
^-|fp||at|^m@2By Marty Bergen |CP|1|AT|^*Htiny.cc/cykc7w^*N|CP||AT|
^B@2You are sitting South and after three passes,|
HT|g|at|^B{|ia|ppp?|at|}|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


ht|f|at|^M@2^Z@3 and you are holding a borderline hand. Should you open, or pass hoping that your next hand will be better?|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT| Using Rule of 15 may help.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


HT|k|AT|^B@2Fourth hand should open if your HCP plus number of spades totals 15 or more. Remember, this applies only to borderline hands; you know what to do with good ones.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

Why are spades crucial here?  You have limited strength and no one opened in front of you. You will therefore be waging a part-score battle in which you will want to outbid the opponents without getting too high. If you own spades, the opponents cannot buy the hand at the two-level.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

Without spades, you might need to compete to the three level. The same is true for the opponents. If they want to compete over your 2@S bid, their two passed hands do not rate to make a nine-trick contract. The more spades you have, the safer it is to open.|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|

What suit should you choose for your opening bid?  No problem! Open the bidding in the same suit you would have with a good hand. Try the following examples to see how easy this is. Remember, add your HCP to the number of spades in your hand.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||
%%%% example 1
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 1|MD|2SAJ74 HK7 DK942 CT63,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^1d|NT|^B@2
Open 1@D.  11 HCP + 4 spades = 15.|mb|1d|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


NT||
%% example 2
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 2|MD|2SAQ965 HA87 D52 C943,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^1s|NT|^B@2
Open 1@S. Use the Rule of 15. You have 10 HCP and five spades — a total of 15. You hope to make a low-level part score.|mb|1s|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


NT||

%% example 3
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 3|MD|2SJ2 HAQ965 DA87 C943,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^p|NT|^B@2
Pass. With 11 HCP and two spades you should not open, even though this hand contains more HCP than the one before. You are concerned that the opponents hold spades, the dominant suit. Being able to make 2@H is worthless if they can bid and make 2@S.|mb|p|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||
%% example 4
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 4|MD|2SQ HKJ6 DA542 CJ8763,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^p|NT|^B@2
Pass. Your 11 HCP plus one spade total 12. You probably can open using the Standard Rule of 20. But Marty Bergen would not open this hand. Try your luck with some new cards.|mb|p|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT|| 
%% example 5
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 5|MD|2S73 HA873 DAKJT64 C2,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^1d|NT|^B@2
Open 1@D. Only use The Rule of 15 when in doubt. With this lovely hand, you have no doubts.|mb|1d|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Whether you are playing for masterpoints or simply for the satisfaction of beating your friends, you prefer plus scores to minus scores. The Rule of 15 is a simple yet reliable tool to decide whether or not to open up what might prove to be a can of worms. You need not feel squeamish when armed with spades.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||AT|
