      The Spades Have It — The Rule of 15      }
^-|fp||at|^n@2By Larry Cohen |CP|1|AT|^*Htiny.cc/fwkc7w^*N|CP||AT|

^B@2Marty Bergen My former bridge partner, Marty Bergen, has 11 conventions named after him. I would like just one "Cohen" convention and I will get to it at the end of this article. Meanwhile, let's talk about 4th seat.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


cs|6|fp|1|AT|
^-
{    FOURTH-SEAT WEAK 2-BIDS    }
^-|fp||at|

After Pass-Pass-Pass, there are some items to consider such as FOURTH-SEAT WEAK 2-BIDS. The normal range for a weak 2-bid is 6-10. But, after three passes, surely you wouldn't open the bidding with 6 points (nor 7, 8, or 9). Really, the range for a 4th-seat weak two should be about 10-14. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||
%%%example 6
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 6|ah|Larry Cohen|MD|2SKQT965 HK3 D98 CKJ5,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^2s|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|After three passes, I'd be happy to open 2@S with the hand as is shown above. This combines preemption with description. Of course, you can't open this hand 2@S in any other seat, because it is too strong. Three-level preempts in fourth seat also show close to opening-bid values.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||
%%%example 7
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 7|ah|Larry Cohen|MD|2S4 HKJ54 DKJ87 CK987,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^p|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|The "book" rule on whether or not to open in 4th seat says to add your HCP to your number of spades. If the total is 15, open the bidding. If less than 15, pass it out. The theory is that it will be a partscore battle, and if your side doesn't have enough of the high-ranking suit, you could easily lose the battle. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|So, you would pass out the hand as is shown above (11 HCP + 1 spade=12)|MB|p|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||
%%%example 8
st||pn||sv|o|rh||ah|Rule 15 - Example 8|ah|Larry Cohen|MD|2SKQT92 HAJ4 D876 C53,,,|mb|ppp?|lb|*bPlease choose your bid. ^^1s|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|But open this hand 1@S|MB|1s|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


AT| (10 HCP + 5 spades=15). This rule is commonly called either "Pearson Points" or "Casino Count."|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||bt||
