      Drury      }
^-|fp||at|^n@2By Larry Cohen |CP|1|AT|^*Htiny.cc/fwkc7w^*N|CP||cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|When you open in 4th seat, you are often on the light side. If you open 1@S with this hand|
ht|g|cs|6|at|^b  {|ih|pSKQT92 HAJ4 D876 C53|at|}|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


ht|m|at|^B, you don't want partner to get too excited. Say that he has a good hand with game interest as is shown below.|
ht|o|at|^b  {|ih|psSAJ5 H76 DJ42 CAJ872|at|}.|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


ht|u|at|^BYou wouldn't want to get too high opposite that hand (8 tricks are the limit). The responder is too strong for 2@S, but rather than bid 3@S, he can bid an artificial 2@C to say he has a limit raise (it is just a coincidence that this example contains a club suit--the Drury 2@C bid says nothing about clubs). Playing modern Drury, the opener would then rebid 2S to say he is not interested in game and the partnership stops safely on the two level. (Technically, this is called "Reverse_Drury," but it is the way "everyone" plays it.)|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


